          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.67,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Most substances reach a temperature where binding wins and atoms localize around crystal sites. Helium is the conspicuous exception at low pressure.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.09,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Absolute zero means the lowest quantum state, not motionless particles with exactly zero kinetic energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.93,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Try to localize one atom tightly around a lattice site. The uncertainty principle forces a broad momentum spread, and therefore nonzero kinetic energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "squeeze"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.6,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "A harmonic estimate captures the floor: every confined mode carries ground-state energy one-half h bar omega.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.49,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Helium atoms are exceptionally light. For the same confinement scale, lower mass makes the zero-point wave packet more delocalized and the kinetic cost larger.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.81,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Meanwhile two neutral helium atoms attract only through a shallow dispersion interaction. There is no gravitational explanation here; the relevant binding is interatomic and unusually weak.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "qualify"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.58,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "At low pressure, the quantum delocalization is large compared with the narrow basin that would hold each atom at a crystal site. The lattice cannot gain enough binding energy to win.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "So cooling removes thermal motion, but it cannot remove the ground-state spread. Helium remains a quantum liquid all the way toward zero kelvin.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.92,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Pressure changes the balance. Compression brings atoms closer and makes the dense ordered phase favorable. Above about twenty-five bar at low temperature, helium-four can crystallize.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compress"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.73,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Do not confuse this with superfluidity. Superfluid flow is another collective quantum phenomenon; zero-point motion already explains why low-pressure helium avoids the solid phase.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "separate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.37,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Helium stays liquid because weak attraction tries to localize atoms while quantum mechanics makes localization costly. Pressure finally tips that competition toward a crystal.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.75,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:28:54"
      }
    },
